Ill maintained and rotting away
Dec 2017 • Solo
The architecture, though splendid and unique, is neglected and doesn't see much crowd other than local children playing inside. One of them told me a story about a prison being there inside the madrasa and prisoners being taken to chaubara thereafter for execution. One of those places that leave you unsettled. Also, the area is predominantly Muslim and women with their head uncovered are rare to come by. Hence, you might want to wear traditional clothes to blend in. I was overwhelmed with requests for selfie and questions regarding my nationality, thanks to my distressed denims and beanie cap which was more uncomfortable than amusing.
Written 24 December 2017
This review is the subjective opinion of a Tripadvisor member and not of TripAdvisor LLC.

Gowrish P
Bengaluru, India158 contributions
Beautiful still. Worth a visit.
Sep 2016 • Family
This is an imposing monument as you drive closer. I was surprised to see how unassuming its location is. Life goes around normal as children play nearby and people go about their daily routine.

Anyhow, it is beautiful. You can spot what's remaining of the colored tiles that must have once adorned this building. An open monument of sorts, you enter the compound and take a walk on the ground floor level.

The main tower still carries some of the old tiles from the fifteenth century. As per records, an accidental explosion destroyed the main dome of this learning center.

The entry is free and a couple of ASI staff oversee this place. There are no guides and you should read the historical snapshot at the main gate.

It should be a quick visit. Place is well kept.
Written 24 September 2016
This review is the subjective opinion of a Tripadvisor member and not of TripAdvisor LLC.
